# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We have to find the lowest common ancestor (LCA) node of two given nodes in the BST.
It means we have to find the **lowest common parent node**.
In a BST, left TreeNode value is smaller than root value and right TreeNode value is greater than the root value.
**Right TreeNode value > Root value > Left TreeNode value**

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
    1. If p and q are smaller than root value, search in left sub-tree.
    2. If p and q are greater, search in right sub-tree.
    3. If p is smaller and q is greater or vice-versa, return root node.

Follow the code below to understand the solution.

         **If this solution helped you, give it an up-vote to help others** 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(logn)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode(int x) { val = x; }
 * }
 */

class Solution {
    public TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        //if both the values are smaller than root value
        //then search in the left sub-tree.
        if (p.val < root.val && q.val < root.val)
        {
            return lowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p, q);
        }
        //if both the values are greater than root value
        //then search in the right sub-tree.
        else if (p.val > root.val && q.val > root.val)
        {
            return lowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p, q);
        }
        //if one value is greater and other is smaller, that means,
        //one node in left sub-tree and other in right sub-tree.
        //In that case, the root is the LCA.
        else
        {
            //hence, return root.
            return root;
        }   

    }
}
```

