# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The code finds the lowest common ancestor (LCA) of two nodes p and q in a binary search tree (BST). The LCA is the deepest node in the BST that has both p and q as descendants (where we allow a node to be a descendant of itself).
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The code defines a recursive function lowestCommonAncestor() that takes three TreeNode pointers root, p, and q as arguments. Within this function, it performs the following steps:

If p->val and q->val are both less than the value of root->val, it means that both p and q are in the left subtree of root. Therefore, the function recursively calls itself with root->left, p, and q as arguments and returns the result.
If p->val and q->val are both greater than the value of root->val, it means that both p and q are in the right subtree of root. Therefore, the function recursively calls itself with root->right, p, and q as arguments and returns the result.
If neither of the above conditions is true, it means that p and q are on different sides of root, or one of them is equal to root. In this case, root is the lowest common ancestor, so it is returned.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The code traverses the BST by recursively going left or right based on the values of p and q. In the worst case, the code visits every node in the BST, resulting in a time complexity of O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the BST.
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(1) since the code uses only a constant amount of additional space, regardless of the input size.
