# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This is a question closed to find the longest common subsequence (LCS)!
[1143. Longest Common Subsequence
](https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-common-subsequence/solutions/3841276/c-recursive-iterative-dp-solutions/)
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
[Please Turn on English subtitles if neccessary]
[https://youtu.be/0jW2q0L8Fw4](https://youtu.be/0jW2q0L8Fw4)
In 2nd approach, we used the usual process for LCS to compute the ascii sum for LCS. Use the following formula
$$
minimumDeleteSum=asciiSum(s1)+asciiSum(s2)-2\times asciiSum(LCS)
$$
which is very similar to the bascic property for finite sets
$$
|difference \ set|=|union|-|interesection|\\
=|s1|+|s2|-2|LCS|
$$
Due to fewer numbers of if-clauses, the speed is slight faster.

The 3rd solution is an iterative buttom up solution which beats 94.62%!
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n1\cdot n2)$$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n1\cdot n2)$$
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string w1, w2;
    int n1, n2;
    vector<vector<int>> dp;

    int lcs(int x, int y){
        if (dp[x][y] != INT_MAX) return dp[x][y];
        if (x == n1 && y == n2) return dp[x][y] = 0;
        if (x == n1) return dp[x][y] = w2[y] + lcs(x, y+1);
        if (y == n2) return dp[x][y] = w1[x] + lcs(x+1, y);

        int sum;
        if (w1[x] == w2[y]) 
            sum = lcs(x+1, y+1);
        else 
            sum = min(lcs(x+1, y) + w1[x], lcs(x, y+1) + w2[y]);

        return dp[x][y] = sum;
    }

    int minimumDeleteSum(string s1, string s2) {
        n1 = s1.size();
        n2 = s2.size();
        w1 = s1;
        w2 = s2;
        dp.assign(n1+1, vector<int>(n2+1, INT_MAX));

        return lcs(0, 0);
    }
};


```
