# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach used here is to build a 2D array `dp` of size `(m+1) x (n+1)`, where `m` is the length of `s1` and `n` is the length of `s2`. Each cell `dp[i][j]` of the array represents the minimum ASCII delete sum for the substrings `s1[0:i]` and `s2[0:j]`. The goal is to find `dp[m][n]`, which will represent the minimum ASCII delete sum for the entire strings `s1` and `s2`.

**Explanation of the Formula:**

The formula `dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + s1.charAt(i - 1)` is used when the characters at the current positions (`i-1` and `j-1`) in both `s1` and `s2` are the same. In this case, no deletions are needed, so we can safely add the ASCII value of the current character to the `dp` value of the previous positions (`i-1` and `j-1`) in the array.

**Explanation of the Else Part:**

The `else` part of the code (`dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1])`) is used when the characters at the current positions in `s1` and `s2` are different. In this case, we need to decide which character to delete to minimize the ASCII sum.

- If we delete the character at position `i-1` in `s1`, then the minimum ASCII delete sum for the current position is equal to `dp[i-1][j]` (i.e., we delete the character in `s1` and consider the substring `s1[0:i-1]` and `s2[0:j]`).
- If we delete the character at position `j-1` in `s2`, then the minimum ASCII delete sum for the current position is equal to `dp[i][j-1]` (i.e., we delete the character in `s2` and consider the substring `s1[0:i]` and `s2[0:j-1]`).

So, the final `dp[i][j]` is the maximum of these two values since we want to minimize the ASCII delete sum.

**Overall Algorithm:**

1. Create a 2D array `dp` of size `(m+1) x (n+1)` and initialize its first row and first column to 0 since empty substrings have a minimum ASCII delete sum of 0.
2. Use nested loops to iterate through the characters of `s1` and `s2`.
3. At each position, apply the formula explained above (`dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + s1.charAt(i - 1)`) when characters are equal, or use the `else` part to decide which character to delete and minimize the ASCII delete sum.
4. The final result is obtained from `dp[m][n]`, which represents the minimum ASCII delete sum for the entire strings `s1` and `s2`.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this dynamic programming approach is O(m * n), where `m` is the length of `s1` and `n` is the length of `s2`. This is because we fill the entire `dp` array of size `(m+1) x (n+1)` using nested loops.
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(m * n) as well, due to the use of the `dp` array.
# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumDeleteSum(String s1, String s2) {
        int m = s1.length();
        int n = s2.length();
        int[][] dp = new int[m + 1][n + 1];

        for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
                if (s1.charAt(i - 1) == s2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + s1.charAt(i - 1);
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);
                }
            }
        }

        int p = 0;
        int q = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            p += s1.charAt(i);
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            q += s2.charAt(i);
        }

        return p + q - 2 * dp[m][n];
    }
}

```

