solutions.content:
This problem has a degree of complexity that can quickly spiral out of control, unless we play a bit smart and store intermediate results as we go, in a classic Dynamic Programming (DP) fashion.

Our general scenario when comparing two characters can be split into two sub-cases:
* if both characters we are comparing are the same, no cost is associated with the removal;
* if they differ, we will take the minimum between what it would cost to remove the current character from the first string and proceed with it, versus doing the same with the current character of the second string.

Visually, displaying only the indexes of each character:

```cpp
01234567 // s1
012345   // s2
```

If the characters at `0` for `s1` and `0` for `s2` match, we are fine and dandy, no costs associated and we proceed to check the cost of having the two strings match as if they both started from position `1`. Visually again, it equates to computing the result to this problem:

```cpp
1234567  // s1
12345    // s2
```

If the characters at `0` for `s1` and `0` for `s2` did not match, we need to compute the minimum between the ASCII code of the character at `0` for `s1` plus matching the strings from position `1` for `s1` and `0` for `s2` match versus the ASCII code of the character at `0` for `s2` plus matching the strings from position `0` for `s1` and `1` for `s2`. The two options, visually:

```cpp
// we will have to take the minimum cost between
// parsing these two options:

// ASCII code of s1[0] + the cost of solving the problem for
1234567  // s1
012345   // s2

- OR -

// ASCII code of s2[0] + the cost of solving the problem for
01234567 // s1
12345    // s2
```

Now, similarly to what we would do with a Fibonacci problem, we can solve this one with a top down approach, starting from the the first two characters and working our way down to the last ones; we will also employ memoisation to avoid re-computing the same results over and over again.

To do so, we will start with a few instance variables:
* `s1` and `s2` will store a copy of our riginal input strings;
* `memo` will be a 2D array and the base for our memoisation effort;
* `l1` and `l2` will store the lengths of the input strings.

In our main function, we will make sure that the first input string is not larger (in order to optimise later for prefilling `memo`) and then populate all the instance variables as expected (with every useful cell in `memo` going to be set to `-1` as a mark of not explored before) and then `return` the result of calling `dfs`.

This helper function will take two indexes `i1` and `i2`, initially defaulted to both be `0` (ie: pointing to the first character) and it will:
* `return` `0` when both indexes are out of boundaries (ie: `i1 == l1 && i2 == l2`, meaning we are done parsing both strings, so no more costs to consider);
* `return` a precomputed value when we have one (ie: `memo[i1][i2] != -1`);
* `return` the sum of all the ASCII codes of the remaining characters in `s2` when `i1` has reached the end of `s1` (ie: `i1 == l1`);
* `return` the sum of all the ASCII codes of the remaining characters in `s1` when `i2` has reached the end of `s2` (ie: `i2 == l2`);
* store the current characters in `c1` and `c2`, respectively;
* compute the current result by checking if `c1 == c2` and:
    * if so, proceed with the value of calling `dfs` with both indexes increased;
    * if not, compute the mininum between the cost of removing `c1` and calling `dfs` advancing only `i1` versus the cost of removing `c2` and calling `dfs` advancing only `i2`;
* store this result in `memo[i1][i2]`;
* `return` it.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

# Code
```cpp
class Solution {
    string s1, s2;
    int memo[1000][1000], l1, l2;
    int dfs(int i1 = 0, int i2 = 0) {
        // base case: end of the run for both
        if (i1 == l1 && i2 == l2) return 0;
        // base case: already computed result
        if (memo[i1][i2] != -1) return memo[i1][i2];
        // base case: end of the run for one
        if (i1 == l1) return memo[i1][i2] = accumulate(begin(s2) + i2, end(s2), 0);
        if (i2 == l2) return memo[i1][i2] = accumulate(begin(s1) + i1, end(s1), 0);
        // general case
        int c1 = s1[i1], c2 = s2[i2];
        return memo[i1][i2] = c1 == c2 ? dfs(i1 + 1, i2 + 1) : min(
            c1 + dfs(i1 + 1, i2),
            c2 + dfs(i1, i2 + 1)
        );
    }
public:
    int minimumDeleteSum(string t1, string t2) {
        // making sure that t1 is not bigger
        if (t1.size() > t2.size()) swap(t1, t2);
        // populating instance variables
        swap(s1, t1);
        swap(s2, t2);
        l1 = s1.size(), l2 = s2.size();
        memset(memo, -1, (l1 + 1) * 1000 * sizeof(int));
        return dfs();
    }
};
```

