[🎨 The ART of Dynamic Programming](https://leetcode.com/discuss/general-discussion/712010/The-ART-of-Dynamic-Programming-An-Intuitive-Approach%3A-from-Apprentice-to-Master)

1. **A**ll possibilities are considered via top-down brute-force depth-first-search
2. **R**emember each subproblem's optimal solution via a DP memo
3. **T**urn the top-down solution upside-down to create the bottom-up solution (starting at top-left with base cases at index 0)
4. **T**urn the top-down solution upside-down to create the bottom-up solution (starting at bottom-right with base cases at index M,N)

---

**Top-Down:** There are 3 choices to consider during a linear scan of each `i`<sup>th</sup>, `j`<sup>th</sup> characters of the input strings `A` and `B` correspondingly:

1. with `A[i]` and `B[j]` at a cost of `0` if `A[i] == B[j]` else `ord(A[i]) + ord(B[j])`
2. without `A[i]` at a cost of `ord(A[i])`
3. without `B[j]` at a cost of `ord(B[j])`

**Base Cases:**

The top-down dfs exhausts the characters of `A` when `i == M`, thus we pay the cost of the remainder of the accumulated ordinal value sum of `B[j..N - 1]`.  Likewise the top-down dfs exhausts the characters of `B` when `j == N`, then we pay the cost of the remainder of the accumulated ordinal value sum of `A[i..M - 1]`.

Note: an astute observer will notice the top-down base case optimization via precomputed prefix ordinal sums.  This is a trivial optimization which was purposefully excluded in favor of simplicity.

**Bottom-Up:** We can iteratively build upon previous optimal solutions from either direction:

1. starting from the top-left and iteratively building to the bottom-right
	* this is the *opposite* direction of the top-down solution's recursive stack unwinding
2. starting from the bottom-right and iteratively building to the top-left
	* this is the *same* direction of the top-down solution's recursive stack unwinding

**Base Cases:**

* if we build solutions starting from the top-left, then we offset the `dp` matrix by `1` index to make room for the explicit base cases at index `0`, ie. `dp[i][j]` refers to `A[i - 1]` and `B[j - 1]`.
* if we build solutions starting from the bottom-right, then we can append the base cases at index `M` and `N` correspondingly.  This is convenient, since we don't need to offset `dp` the matrix by `1` as we relatively refer to each `i`<sup>th</sup> and `j`<sup>th</sup> index of the input strings `A` and `B` correspondingly, ie. `dp[i][j]` refers to `A[i]` and `B[j]`

---

**Kotlin Solutions:**

1. **A**ll possibilities are considered via top-down brute-force depth-first-search
```
class Solution {
    fun minimumDeleteSum(A: String, B: String): Int {
        var (M, N) = listOf(A.length, B.length)
        var ord = { x: Char -> x.toByte().toInt() }
        fun go(i: Int = 0, j: Int = 0): Int {
            if (i == M) return B.slice(j until N).map{ ord(it) }.sum()!!
            if (j == N) return A.slice(i until M).map{ ord(it) }.sum()!!
            var a = go(i + 1, j + 1) + if (A[i] == B[j]) 0 else ord(A[i]) + ord(B[j])
            var b = go(i + 1, j) + ord(A[i])
            var c = go(i, j + 1) + ord(B[j])
            return listOf(a, b, c).min()!!
        }
        return go()
    }
}
```

2. **R**emember each subproblem's optimal solution via a DP memo
```
class Solution {
    fun minimumDeleteSum(A: String, B: String): Int {
        var (M, N) = listOf(A.length, B.length)
        var m = mutableMapOf<String, Int>()
        var ord = { x: Char -> x.toByte().toInt() }
        fun go(i: Int = 0, j: Int = 0): Int {
            if (i == M) return B.slice(j until N).map{ ord(it) }.sum()!!
            if (j == N) return A.slice(i until M).map{ ord(it) }.sum()!!
            var k = "$i,$j"
            if (!m.contains(k)) {
                var a = go(i + 1, j + 1) + if (A[i] == B[j]) 0 else ord(A[i]) + ord(B[j])
                var b = go(i + 1, j) + ord(A[i])
                var c = go(i, j + 1) + ord(B[j])
                m[k] = listOf(a, b, c).min()!!
            }
            return m[k]!!
        }
        return go()
    }
}
```

3. **T**urn the top-down solution upside-down to create the bottom-up solution (starting at top-left with base cases at index 0)
```
class Solution {
    fun minimumDeleteSum(A: String, B: String): Int {
        var (M, N) = listOf(A.length, B.length)
        var ord = { x: Char -> x.toByte().toInt() }
        var dp = Array(M + 1) { IntArray(N + 1) { 0 } }
        for (i in 1..M) dp[i][0] = dp[i - 1][0] + ord(A[i - 1])
        for (j in 1..N) dp[0][j] = dp[0][j - 1] + ord(B[j - 1])
        for (i in 1..M) {
            for (j in 1..N) {
                var a = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + if (A[i - 1] == B[j - 1]) 0 else ord(A[i - 1]) + ord(B[j - 1])
                var b = dp[i - 1][j] + ord(A[i - 1])
                var c = dp[i][j - 1] + ord(B[j - 1])
                dp[i][j] = listOf(a, b, c).min()!!
            }
        }
        return dp[M][N]
    }
}
```

4. **T**urn the top-down solution upside-down to create the bottom-up solution (starting at bottom-right with base cases at index M,N)
